        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>SPT 0346-52 will be observed in the HD line (rest freq. measured very accurately recently in lab at  2674.9861 GHz) at its redshifted frequency of 401.89697 GHz (Band 8) (or wavelength = 745.94667 microns)
at this redshift, a line width of 500 km/s = 0.67029GHz. 

The estimate of the observing time is based on an assumed molecular mass of H2 molecules of 1.4E^11 M_sun, or 3.3e^63 molecules of H2. 
Adopting a roughly 70% primordial D/H abundance ratio the N(H20/N(HD) ratio would be 4 x 10^-5, (or 2e-5 for HD/2H2= D/H ratio). Further assuming, based on a simple model of the excitation of HD at 85-120K the N_0-1 = 1/3 N(HD) is assumed. Using the fact that the Eistein coefficient for HD1-0 = 5.12e-8 /s we can calculate the HD 1-0 photon luminosity from the cloud to be 10^35 W. Assuming a luminosity 
distance of 5389Mpc (assuming standard lamdba CDM cosmology and H=70) we get a total flux at the earth in the line of 1.5e-20 W/m^2 after multiplying by 5 for lensing amplification.  Spreading over a 500 km/s assumed velocity width we get a 2.3mJy peak flux. This converts to a 9-sigma detection in 100 km/s channels in Band 8 with a 3.5 total on-source time. With overheads (which are high at Band 8) the total time is 7.5 hrs. We note that if the fraction of 
HD which is hot and dense is lower by a factor of two or more we will smooth the spectrum to achieve a detection. 

Although we are confident that the published (Weiss et al 2013) redshift is correct 5.6559(4) we straddle two 2GHz IFs across the line shifting each by 9 (2000GHz/256channel) channels of the correlator
(703.12MHz), so that we can add together the two bands with perfect alignment of channels. This results is an offset of the expected line from each of the overlapping IFs of 525 km/s- so the line will be fully covered in each band without getting to near the edges(in case of band roll-off). We thus cover a large velocity range around the line center when both IRs are added (3.4GHz = 2541 km/s).  

 
  
 </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
