    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>By analogy with the detection of powerful warm molecular hydrogen in turbulent gas in nearby compact groups and radio galaxies, we propose to search for emission from the lowest transition 0-0R(0)112micron line of deuterated molecular hydrogen (HD) in one of the most powerful, strongly lensed star forming galaxies found to date at z = 5.6. Although HD is much less abundant than molecular hydrogen, with a diploe moment, it is a powerful coolant in primordial gas, and is found associated with dense shocked gas in the local universe. We target SPT 0346-52, a lensed system (mag. factor 5.4) which contains ~1.4 x 10^11 M_sun of likely warm H_2. The very powerful nature of the CO and H2O lines detected by ALMA indicate that this is an ideal test case for the detection of shock-heated HD in high-z objects. The detection of HD will open up a potential new channel, and calibration point, for studying turbulent systems at high-z. Detection of HD is aided by an expected increase in D/H abundance with z, compared with local values, as well as a the fact that the line is shifted into less noisy ALMA bands with increasing z. </prp:abstract>
